@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.01 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.01 How many floppy drives can I have?

            The most external floppy drives you can use is 4. They must be
        capable of daisy chaining, and must have enough power to
        function. The Amiga can easily handle one external floppy drive,
        but any more should run on their own power supplies. You may
        wish to buy a larger power supply if you wish to do this. If
        you have an Amiga with multiple drive bays, you can fit two
        internal floppies. If you have only one drive bay, such as in
        an A500, you can only have one internal floppy in addition to
        the 4 external floppies.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.02 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.02 Does the Amiga support high density floppy disks?

            The A4000 includes a 1.76 megabyte floppy drive which also
        reads IBM 1.44 megabyte and IBM 720k disks. This floppy drive
        should work with most Amigas. Some A3000's in Australia were
        shipped with high density floppy drives. Applied Engineering
        also manufactured a high density floppy drive, but it did
        not sell well due to its high price. The Amiga high density
        drive from CBM sells for under $100. Many people have used
        standard IBM high density drives using a special device driver.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.03 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.03 Why does the floppy drive click when it has no disk?

            The floppy drive clicks every second or so since it is
        waiting for a disk to be inserted. Some 5.25" drives use
        an older system which requires the user to execute the
        @{" DiskChange " link diskchange} command whenever loading a new disk.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.04 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.04 How do I make my floppy drive stop clicking?

            There are two ways to stop the drive from clicking. One
        simple way is to insert a disk in the drive. Another way is
        to use one of many software patches that stops the drive from
        clicking even when no disk is inserted. These patches often
        have names like NoClick, StopClick, or AntiClick. When using
        these or multi-purpose software patches, ensure that it is
        compatible with your current OS revision.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.05 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.05 Should my floppy drive use its own power supply?

            If you are using a computer with multiple internal floppy
        drives, as long as you have a power connector you should be
        safe. However, when using external floppy drives on a computer
        such as the A500, A600, A1000, or A1200, there may not be
        enought power to support the external drive. A general rule is
        to have the Amiga support no more than one external floppy
        drive and no more than 3 megabytes of memory. If you choose
        to expand, you should look for either a higher powered power
        supply, additional power supplies for external drives, or drives
        with lower power consumption.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.06 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.06 Is it possible to write protect a floppy drive?

            Some floppy drives offer virus protection via a hardware
        switch on the drive that does not allow anything to write to
        a drive. Or you may use the @{" Lock " link lock} command.

@endnode
