@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.07 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.07 What are the advantages or disadvantages of floppy drives?

            Advantages:

                small and convenient
                protective self-enclosed case
                easily transportable
                may be removed for storage and replaced
                may be write protected in hardware
                lower price per megabyte ratio
                less expensive per unit


            Disadvantages:

                slower access times than other media
                smaller capacities
                more likely to receive disk errors due to handling
                disks exposed to air, dust, water
                drives exposed to air and dust
                warranties expire sooner
                too little space for modern applications

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.08 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.08 What is a floppy disk made of?

            Most 3.5" floppy disks are composed of many parts, but the
        actual data surface that the computer uses is often made of a
        material similar to kevlar. This surface must be magnetic, and
        it must be capable of holding data for daily use.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.09 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.09 In what ways can a floppy disk become damaged?

            Punctures - Any damage to the writing surface of a disk
                may damage data or cause the entire disk to be unusable.
                Older disks, such as 5.25" or 8" floppies, did not have
                the strong protective case that 3.5" disks have, so this
                was a big problem. The writing surface was exposed, and
                it was thin enough to be pierced by a stapler or other
                object by a computer-illiterate user.

            Finger Prints - A source of problems for users of 5.25" disks,
                this is no longer a cause to data loss for most 3.5" disk
                users since 3.5" disks include a small sliding door which
                protects the disk itself. Oil from human finger prints
                may cause damage to the surface.

            Water - In general, water is harmful to the disk surface,
                and you should never place a damp or wet disk into a
                floppy drive. However, as an anecdote, at one time I
                accidentally dropped a disk in a water puddle and the
                disk still retained its data. However, I would advise
                that any water damaged disks have the data recovered as
                soon as the disk is dried, and discard or do not rely upon
                the water-damaged disk.

            Heat - One of the largest causes of data failure is due to
                extreme temperatures. Most disks cannot withstand any
                temperatures below freezing or above 120 degrees
                Fahrenheit. They have however been capable of surviving
                most trips through the postal service in all types of
                weather.

            Sunlight - Direct sunlight will cause damage to a floppy
                disk in a matter of minutes. This will cause the kevlar
                disk to warp and otherwise lose data. Any disk exposed
                to prolonged sunlight will become damaged beyond
                usability. If sunlight is a problem, you may wish to
                wrap your disks in aluminum foil, as it is capable of
                reflecting the sunlight and the heat from it.

            Magnetics - Any electrical device will produce a magnetic
                field, including the computer itself. The biggest
                culprit to data loss is probably due to magnetic fields,
                such as found in airport security systems, computer
                equipment, stereo equipment, televisions, etc. The best
                way to safeguard is to keep disks stored away from
                these fields, and don't lie them on your desktop near your
                monitor.

            Time - As time goes by, disks will lose data. The average
                disk may have a lifespan of quite a few years. Although
                it is possible for floppy disks to work continuously
                for a period of ten years or more, eventually they will
                fail and require replacement.

            Normal Usage - Disks can become damaged simply by using them.
                For example, removing a disk before the drive is done
                writing to it may damage it. Also, placing the computer
                at an angle, in a verticle position, or upside-down,
                may misalign the read/write heads. If the heads are out
                of alignment, you will have trouble reading disks from
                other computers, and other computers will have trouble
                reading your disks.

@endnode
