@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.12 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.12 Why do my disks get so many errors?

            While some disks inherenlt have errors due to poor materials
        and design, there are other causes of frequent errors. If the
        read/write heads land on the surface of the disk too many times
        they may damage it. Errors can also be caused if dust, water,
        hair, fingerprints, or scratches appear on the disk. An error
        can occur if the disk is ejected during a data write, which is
        a common problem on slower Amigas using the 68000 chip, which
        pauses before the disk may be ejected. Last of all, using a disk
        that is not designed for a particular drive may cause it to
        become unreliable, such as a high density disk in a low density
        drive.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node FAQ.Floppy_Drives.3.13 "Floppy Drive Questions"
@toc FAQ.Floppy_Drives

    3.13 What is the difference between a soft error and a hard error?

            A soft error is a recoverable error that occurs on a disk,
        such as the data becoming misaligned due to magnetic interference
        or an error in writing the data. A hard error is a physical
        problem with the disk that cannot be fixed, such as the media
        deteriorating to the point where it no longer holds data, such as
        from a scratch or dust.

@endnode
